Calculate reflectivity

Preliminary values per wavelength

This function multiplies the irradiance of the sun * the reflectance at each wavelength

# 1) Define the following function to find the multiplication

Find.multiplication<-function(s){
  vector2<-rep("NA", length(s[ , 1]))
  for( i in 2 : length(s) - 1){
    for (y in 1 : length(s[ , 1])){
      vector2[y] <- s[y, i] * s[y, "Sun"] # multiply each column by the last one
    }
    s[i] <- as.numeric(vector2) 
  }
  return(s)
}

# 2) Apply 
PrelValuesRefl <- Find.multiplication(Reflectance) 

# 3) Clean up preliminary values for reflectivity
PrelValuesRefl <-
  PrelValuesRefl %>% 
  dplyr::select (-wl, # the wavelengths were altered, eliminate
          -Sun) %>% # Sun irradiance not required anymore, eliminate
  mutate (wl = Reflectance$wl) %>%  # add the correct wavelength column
  dplyr::select(wl, everything()) %>% # set the wl column as column 1
  as.rspec(.) # convert to rspec object

Divide the vectors with the AUC per species, by the AUC of the sun for each spectral range. This step is useful to express reflectivity as the percentage of light comming from the sun, reflected by the beetle on each spectral range

  "R_ALL"= B1ALL/B1SunALL,

Calculate Absorptivity

This parameter is calculated as Abs = 100 - (Reflectivity + Transmissivity)

Reflect_sub <- 
  Reflectivity %>% 
  filter(ind %in% (Transmissivity$ind)) %>% 
  arrange(ind)


Optical <- # A data frame with the 3 optical properties
  data.frame(Reflect_sub,Transmissivity) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-ind.1) %>% 
  mutate(
    A_ALL = 100 - (R_ALL + T_ALL), # Absorptivity for VIS+NIR 
    A_VIS = 100 - (R_VIS + T_VIS), # Absorptivity for VIS
    A_NIR = 100 - (R_NIR + T_NIR) # Absorptivity for NIR
  )

PCA

Extract Components

cord <- cor(EVar) # default: pearsons correlation coeficient
N <- dim(EVar)[1] # number of observations
cortest.bartlett(cord,n=N) # Are the variables correlated? Yes p < 0.05
## $chisq
## [1] 1693.035
## 
## $p.value
## [1] 0
## 
## $df
## [1] 21
eigVal <- eigen(cord) # Extract eigen values
vectorev <- eigVal$vectors # vector with the eigen values
# Extract components
compv <- prcomp(EVar, retx=TRUE, center=TRUE, scale. = TRUE) # components
load<-compv$rotation # Loadings matrix

Consolidated Data Frames

Reflectivity

Include the additional variables: NIR-VIS residuals, Size and Species name as written in the phylogeny

NIR - VIS residuals:

This step in required because visible and NIR reflectivity are expected to be correlated. Using the residuals of the correlation between these two properties is useful to explore if NIR reflectivity is driven by pressures different than the ones affecting visible (mainly thermoregulation)

#Plot of the correlation between NIR and VIS reflectivity
ggplot(data = Reflectivity, aes(x = R_VIS, y = R_NIR))+
  geom_point(size=3,alpha=0.4, pch=21,
             col="black",
             fill= "#39BEB1")+
  geom_smooth (method="lm", col="black")+
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("Reflectivity in VIS (%)") +
  ylab("Reflectivity in NIR (%)")

# Linear model
NIRVISMod1 <- lm (Reflectivity$R_NIR ~ Reflectivity$R_VIS)

If interaction was not included:

PC1 does not predict reflectivity. PC2 predicts VIS reflectivity and Residuals, but with oposite pattern: Hot and arid environments are correlated with high reflectivity in VIS, and lower (negative) NIR residuals. Size has an effect in total, nir and vis reflectivity but not in the residuals.

Interaction included in all models:

TOT -

Size explains total reflectivity: overall, larger beetles reflect more light

VIS -

size explains reflectivity in VIS: larger beetles generally reflect more vis light.

PC1 and PC1-Size-Interaction explain reflectivity in VIS: Beetles in humid environments reflect more VIS. And this effect is likely to be more pronounced in small beetles.

PC2 explains reflectivity in VIS: Beetles in hot/arid environments are reflect more VIS. And this pattern prevails regardless of the size of the beetle.

Res -

PC2 and PC2-Size interaction explain NIR residuals: Beetles in hot/arid environments seem to reflect less NIR than the value expected by the simple correlation VIS-NIR. And this pattern is more pronounced in small beetles.

p4

MCMC Model

This model tests if the correlations we found in the previous step remain after correcting by phylogeny. This models considers the instraspecific differences in both the reflectivity and the location

Note:

We use an inverse Wishart prior for the variances and parameter expanded priors for the random effects. Specifically, we use the inverse-gamma prior (V=1) with scale and shape equal to 0.001 (nu=0.002). For parameter expanded priors, we use V=1, nu=1, alpha.mu=0, which is equivalent to a proper Cauchy prior for the standard deviation with scale equal to square-root(alpha.V.). Here we used alpha.V=25^2 following Gelman.2006.

With V=1 these distributions are equivalent to inverse gamma distributions with shape and scale parameters set to nu/2.

Set priors for MCMC

# Include 2 Gs = 2 random factors:
# 1) species (multiple individuals per species) = "phylogeny_name" 
# 2) phylogeny (phylogenetic relatedness) = "animal" 

prior <- list(
  R = list(V = 1, n = 0.002),
  G = list(
    G1 = list(V = 1, n = 1, alpha.mu = 0, alpha.V = 25^2),
    G2 = list(V = 1, n = 1, alpha.mu = 0, alpha.V = 25^2)
  )
)

Set up the model

mcmcmodel <- Reflectance ~ PC1 + PC2 + size + PC1*size + PC2*size

Parameters for the model: nitt = 3000, burnin = 500, thin = 1. Set up a shared inverseA and sub-datasets for the MCC tree analysis

AinvTA.MCC <- inverseA(MCCtree)$Ainv

ALLDataSet$animal <- factor(ALLDataSet$phylogeny_name)

NIRDataSet$animal <- factor(NIRDataSet$phylogeny_name)

VISDataSet$animal <- factor(VISDataSet$phylogeny_name)

ResDataSet$animal <- factor(ResDataSet$phylogeny_name)

Note: In the plots, the trace should span across the y axis to show that the model have reached all the possibilities.

In the density plots, if the center of the distribution is away from zero, the variable is effective on the dependent variable. The n value in the figure equals to the trees we saved from the model, here: 3000(nitt) - 500(burnin) = 2500.

ALL Reflectivity

mcmcModMCC_ALL <- MCMCglmm(mcmcmodel,
  random = ~ animal + phylogeny_name,
  # account for phylogeny info and species as random factors
  prior = prior,
  ginverse = list(animal = AinvTA.MCC),
  # because "animal" that accounts for phylogeny
  data = ALLDataSet,
  family = "gaussian", # depends on the distribution of the parameter 
  nitt = 3000, burnin = 500, thin = 1, # just to get the chains start
  # Since this is only one round, increase this number to increase reliability
  pl = T,
  pr = F,
  verbose = F,
  singular.ok = T
)

Model Convergency

obtain the ``trace of the sampling (to check for convergence and auto-correlation) and posterior density of each parameter.

If the model has converged there should be no trend in the time series. If its not spanning all over, it means that the trace for the residual variance has strong auto-correlation and needs to be run for longer.

In the density plots, if the center of the distribution away from zero, meaning that the variable is effective on the dependent variable. The n value in the figure equals to the trees we saved from the model, nitt# - burnin#.

Set priors for MCMC

# Include 1 Gs = 1 random factors:
# 1) phylogeny (phylogenetic relatedness) = "animal" 

prior.sp2 <- list(
  R = list(V = 1, n = 0.002),
  G = list(G1 = list(V = 1, n = 1, alpha.mu = 0, alpha.V = 25^2))
)

Prepare data sets

The NIR mystery (Old calculations)

Our hypothesis was that more exposed arid environments would correlate to higher NIR/vis Ratio, since higher NIR could be used for thermoregulation. However, we found the opposite pattern: No correlation between NIR and PC2, and lower NIR/Vis ratio in more arid environments:

ggplot(Cons, aes(x = PC2, y = Ratio))+
  geom_point(size=3,alpha=0.4, pch=21,
             col="black",
             fill= "#762A83")+
  geom_smooth (method="lm")+
  theme_bw()+
  ylim (0,23)+
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Accent")+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

My explanation: In these beetles higher values of NIR/VIS ratio are found more often in individuals with moderate NIR and very low vis, rather than in beetles with high NIR and moderate vis.
Thus, higher ratio is inversely correlated with the total reflectivity, and not useful in arid environments with high radiation.

A plot to illustrate this:

ggplot(Cons, aes( full, Ratio)) + 
  geom_point(size=3, alpha=0.3, pch=21,
             col= "black",
             fill = "#762A83") + 
  xlim(10,56) + 
  ylim(0,22)+
  theme_bw()

So maybe, they all have high NIR reflectance and the ones in more extreme environments would need also to have high VIS reflectance.

  • Compare with other groups of beetles or insects here.

Do they all have very high NIR reflecttivity?

p <- ggplot(Cons, aes( NIR, vis)) + 
  geom_point(size=3, alpha=0.3, col= "#762A83") + 
  xlim(0,100) + 
  ylim(0,70)+
  theme_bw()
ggExtra::ggMarginal(p, type = "histogram", fill="gray")

Not really, there is a lot of variability, but it is important to highlight that the average reflectivity for NIR is r mean(Cons$NIR) %. As shown in the following plot, the highest values of reflectivity in this group are in the NIR spectral band, therefore it is likely to contribute significantly to the results in the total reflectivity (including all wavelengths).

Diagnostics <- 
  Cons %>% 
  dplyr::select (full, NIR, vis) %>% 
  rename (All = full,
          VIS = vis) %>% 
  gather (key = spectralband, 
          value = Reflectivity)   # prepare for ggplot

  theme_bw()+
